<s1 id=MComposeFormatMenu>Mailer Compose Format Menu
<location id=dtmailComposeWindowmenubarFormat>&empty;<\location>

	<idx>Compose window Format menu<sort>compose window format menu<\idx>
	<idx>Format menu:on Compose window<sort>format menu:on compose window<\idx>
	<idx>Word Wrap:on Compose window Format menu<sort>word wrap:on compose window format menu<\idx>
	<idx>Settings:on Compose window Format menu<sort>settings:on compose window format menu<\idx>
	<idx>Change Char Set:on Compose window Format menu<sort>change char set:on compose window format menu<\idx>
	<idx>Use Template:on Compose window Format menu<sort>use template:on compose window format menu<\idx>
	<idx>Use Draft:on Compose window Format menu<sort>use draft:on compose window format menu<\idx>
	<idx>Include Signature:on Compose window Format menu<sort>include signature:on compose window format menu<\idx>
	<idx>Vacation Message:on Compose window Format menu<sort>Vacation Message:on compose window format menu<\idx>
	<idx>Aliases:on Compose window Format menu<sort>aliases:on compose window format menu<\idx>
	<idx>Add Bcc:on Compose window Format menu<sort>add bcc:on compose window format menu<\idx>

<p gentity=Mailer-Compose-Format-Menu gposition=left>
<newline>&empty;

<term nogloss>Word Wrap<\term> toggles the text entry mode that causes 
the right margins of lines to automatically wrap at the right edge of 
the window.<newline>

<term nogloss>Settings<\term> displays a dialog box for setting margins 
and paragraph alignment, and applying format settings to your message.<newline>

<term nogloss>Change Char Set<\term> converts the text in the 
Compose window to the character set that you select, the name of which 
is displayed in the footer of the window.  Continuously choosing this 
item cycles through the character set choices that are available (for 
example, ISO-2022-JP, EUC-JP, ISO-8859-1, and US-ASCII).  The item 
named Default Char Set is the default encoding for your machine.<newline>

<term nogloss>Use Template<\term> accesses the templates you have created for 
use in mail messages, and loads the one that you choose from the submenu 
in the Compose window.<newline>

<term nogloss>Use Draft<\term> accesses the drafts you have created for 
use in mail messages, and loads the one that you choose from the submenu 
in the Compose window.<newline>

<term nogloss>Include Signature<\term> places the signature that you have
set up for your outgoing messages at the end of the message.<newline>

<term nogloss>Signature<\term> opens the Signature Options dialog box where 
you can create or change the signature for your outgoing messages.<newline>

<term nogloss>Vacation Message<\term> opens the Vacation Message Options 
dialog box where you can set the vacation notifier option to respond to 
incoming messages when you are away from your mail.<newline>

<term nogloss>Aliases<\term> opens the Aliases Options dialog box where you
can add, change, or remove your own private distribution lists, known as 
aliases.<newline>

<term nogloss>Add Bcc<\term> adds the Bcc (Blind Carbon Copy) header to your
Compose window.  You can then send a copy of a message to someone without 
those on the To or Cc line seeing that person's address.  The Bcc button
menu lists all your aliases.  You can choose one or more of these aliases 
as the Bcc recipients for your message.

<p>If you have added others headers beside Bcc (such as Add Return-Receipt-To or Add Reply-To), they also appear on the Format menu as in the example.<newline>

<!--
<lablist width=2in>
<labheads> \Use \ To
\ Word Wrap \	Toggle the text entry mode that causes lines
to automatically wrap at the edge of the message. Word Wrap is based on
72-column formatting. This may cause problems if the sender has word 
wrap turned on and the recipient window is a different size.

\ Settings \	Display a dialog box for setting margins and paragraph 
		alignment, and applying format settings to your message. 
<p indent gentity=Generic-Mouse-Click ghyperlink=survival-skills-mouse glinktype=Definition>.

\ Templates \	Quickly access the templates (text files) you created for 
		using in your mail messages. See <xref MailTemplatesTA> for 
		more information.		

\ Add Bcc: \	Put up the Bcc (Blind Carbon Copy) header in 
		your Compose window.  <emph>Bcc<\emph> enables you to send a copy of 
		a message to someone without those on the <emph>To<\emph> or <emph>Cc<\emph>
		line seeing the user's address. If you added other headers beside Bcc, 
		they show up here.  See <xref ComposeWindowOptions> for more information.
<\lablist>
