<\figure>
<newline>&empty;
 
<!--
<term nogloss>Left Margin<\term>
<list plain tight>
<item>The number of characters to indent the selected text from
the left edge of the window. The default is 0.
<\list>
<term nogloss>Right Margin<\term>
<list plain tight>
<item>The number of characters to indent the selected text from
the right edge of the window. The default is 80.
<\list>
The alignment setting determines how the text is justified.
<lablist>
\ Align \
\ Left \ Justifies the text lines on the left margin.
\ Right \ Justifies the text lines on the right margin.
\ Justify \ Aligns the text in a block style with
equal left and right margins.
\ Center \ Centers text lines between the margins.
<\lablist>
 
<note>
You can change settings for individual messages by choosing Settings
from the Format menu in the Compose window.
<\note>
 
<lablist>
\ Word Wrap \ If this option is selected, hard line breaks are inserted at
the
    places where the message text wraps.  If Word Wrap is not selected, the
    text appears as one long line, the way the sender inserted soft line breaks.
-->
 
<!--
<lablist>
\ Show Attachment List \    Shows or hides the attachment list at
                the bottom of Compose windows.
<\lablist>
-->
 
<term nogloss>Compose Window Width<\term>
<list plain tight>
<item>This option determines how wide the Compose window is.  You can
increase or decrease the default of 80 characters.
<\list>
 
<term nogloss>Show Attachment List<\term>
<list plain tight>
<item>This option shows or hides the attachment list at the bottom of
the Compose window.
<\list>
 
<term nogloss>Indent Characters for Included Message<\term>
<list plain tight>
<item>This option specifies the characters that precede each line
of a reply-include message.  The default value is an angle 
bracket (>).  Tabs are not accepted as indented characters, 
but spaces are acceptable.
<\list>
 
<term nogloss>Dead Letter Folder<\term>
<list plain tight>
<item>Mailer saves messages you are composing every 10 minutes.  These messages
are saved in the folder specifed in the Dead Letter Folder field,
for example: <var>HomeDirectory<\var><computer>/DeadLetters<\computer>.
If you are in the middle of composing a message when Mailer crashes,
you can recover a copy of the message from the <computer>mail.dead.letter.<\computer><var>number<\var> file in this folder. 
<\list>
 
<term nogloss>Custom Header Fields (Available on Format Menu)<\term>
<list plain tight>
<item>Use this option to add custom header names to the Format menu
in the Compose window.  Your header always contains To, Subject, and 
Cc fields.  Some useful headers you might want to add are:
 
<lablist>
\ Bcc \         Stands for Blind Carbon Copy.  If you list an addressee here,
                Mailer sends a copy to that addressee without the knowledge 
                of the recipients in the To or Cc list.
<p>This item appears as a default on the Compose Format menu.  However,
you can add addressees in the Default Value field to specify Bcc recipients
for your outgoing mail, such as yourself.
\ Precedence:junk \ If you use this header, messages the mail
            system cannot send are not bounced back to you.
            This header is handy if you are sending out a message to a
            large alias and do not want to receive notices every
            time a message cannot be delivered to an individual.
\ Reply-To \    If you use this header, the reply
            is sent to the email address in the Reply-To header
            field instead of being sent to the sender of the
            message. This header is handy if you want to forward a
            message sent to you by mistake and you want responses
            to go to the original sender only.
\ Return-Receipt-To \   Sending a message with this header gives you
            a return receipt from the mail system when the
            message is successfully delivered to the recipient.
<\lablist>
<\list>
 
<term nogloss>Header Name<\term>
<list plain tight>
<item>The label for a field you want to add to the headers available from the Format menu in the Compose window (for example, Receipt).
<\list>
 
<term nogloss>Default Value<\term>
<list plain tight>
<item>The default entry for a defined header field (for example, Return-Receipt-To).
 
<lablist>
\ Add \     Adds the value you typed into the Header Name and
            Default Value fields to the scrolling list.
\ Delete \  Deletes the selected label from the scrolling list.
\ Change \  Changes the selected label to the different values
            in the Header Name and Default Value fields.  The
            change is reflected in the scrolling list.
<\lablist>
<\list>
 
