Choose Advanced from the Options menu to set some advanced mail defaults.

<newline>&empty;
<figure nonumber entity=Mailer-Advanced>
<\figure>
<newline>&empty;

<term nogloss>Warn if message exceeds nn Kbytes<\term> 
<list plain tight>
<item>When this option is selected, if a message that you intend to send 
exceeds a certain size (1000 Kbytes by default), Mailer posts a warning 
message.  This option is off by default.
<\list>
 
<term nogloss>Show confirmation notices<\term> 
<list plain tight>
<item>When this option is selected, every time you make edits in a Compose
window and then quit the window, Mailer posts a confirmation message
that the text will be deleted.

<p>With this option on, Mailer also displays a warning when you
send a mail message after doing one of the following:

<list bullet>
<item>Choosing either Continue Composing Draft from the Compose menu or 
Use Draft from the Compose Format menu and loading a draft in the Compose 
window

<item>Saving text in the Compose window as a draft message
<\list>

<p>The warning states that the draft will be deleted as soon as the
Compose window closes.
<\list>

<note>
If you turn off this option, Mailer does not display either
of these warning messages, and you could potentially lose data when you:

<list bullet>
<item>Have unsaved edits in the Compose window when you close it, in which 
case the text will be deleted.

<item>Send a message after working on a draft in the Compose window,
in which case the draft in your file system will be deleted.
<\list>
<\note>

<!--
<term nogloss>Use strict MIME character encoding<\term> 
<list plain tight>
<item> If you or a correspondent of yours find that messages 
are often corrupted or damaged, your standard message transport 
may be at fault.  Select this option to see if MIME character encoding
solves this problem.  

<item>You can select this option if you know that you and the people you
exchange messages with are running a fully compliant MIME package.
If you are uncertain, check with your system administrator.

If you fall into neither of the categories above, leave this option 
unselected.
<\list>
-->

<term nogloss>Use network aware mail file locking<\term> 
<list plain>
<item>Mailer can detect and prevent two different instances of itself
from opening the same mail file at the same time when both instances
of Mailer and the file are all on the same machine.

A network-aware mail file locking protocol is available that uses
ToolTalk to coordinate instances of Mailer running from more 
than one machine, or mail files accessed over the network.

<item>Mailer can only change this option when first opening a mail file.
If you change this option when a mail file is open, you are given
three choices:

<list bullet>
<item>You can close the current mail file and reopen it, making the new
locking technique take effect immediately.
<item>You can continue editing the current mail file. The new locking
technique will take effect the next time you open a mail file.
<item>You can cancel the Apply and return to setting options.
<\list>
<\list>

<term nogloss>Keep empty mailboxes<\term><newline>
<list plain tight>
<item>Mailer usually deletes empty mailboxes.  If you want to retain 
mailboxes even if you delete all the messages inside, deselect 
this option.
<\list>

<term nogloss>Save messages in MIME format<\term><newline>
<list plain tight>
<item>Mailer saves your incoming messages in MIME format by default.  
To leave your messages in their current formats, deselect this option.
<\list>

<location id=dtmailSendMailInMIME>&empty;<\location>
<term nogloss>Send mail in MIME format<\term><newline>
<list plain tight>
<item>Mailer sends messages in MIME format by default.  To send an individual
message in Sun Mail Tool format, choose Sun Mail Tool from the Send As
submenu in the File menu in the Compose window.  To change the default
format to Sun Mail Tool, deselect this option.
<\list>

<term nogloss>Host to send mail from<\term><newline>
<list plain tight>
<item>This is the host on which your Inbox is located.  If you have a
local Inbox, the default is your local host; if your Inbox
is on an IMAP server, the default is that IMAP server name.

<p>You may want to type a different name in the text field if:
<list bullet tight>
<item>The machine you are using cannot send mail.
  
<item>You are using IMAP to log in and send mail from different machines.
	
<item>You are sending mail from a machine that uses a dialup connection
to access the network, such as a point-to-point protocol (PPP) or
Integrated Services Digital Network (ISDN) connection.
<\list>
    
<p>For example, if you type <computer>my-host<\computer> in the text field, 
the From header in your outgoing messages will read <computer>From: 
user-name@my-host.<\computer>  The replies from your recipients will then 
be sent to the machine <computer>my-host<\computer>.
<\list>

<term nogloss>When I Reply to All:<\term><newline>
<term nogloss>Ignore host name in address<\term><newline>
<term nogloss>Include me<\term> 
<list plain tight>
<item>These options determine when your email address is included 
in the To and Cc fields of a Reply to All recipients of a message that
you send, and what form your email address takes.

<item>To include your email address in the To and Cc fields of a Reply 
to All outgoing message in the form 
<var>yourname<\var>@<var>hostname<\var>, leave these two options 
unselected.

<item>To remove your email address from the To and Cc fields, select <quote>Ignore host name in address<\quote>, but leave <quote>Include 
me<\quote> unselected.

<item>To include your email address in the To or Cc fields 
(if it would ordinarily appear there) in all the forms it might take,
including your login address (such as <var>yourname<\var>@<var>hostname<\var>), select Include me.

The Ignore host name in address option only applies if the 
Include me option is not selected.  It determines whether
your email address is recognized in all forms that include your login
address, or only in the form <var>yourname<\var>@<var>hostname<\var>.    
<\list>
 
<term nogloss>Treat the following as:<\term> 
<list plain tight>
<item>When this option is selected, the names in the scrolling list are 
considered equivalent to your login name.  You can add other names or aliases 
for which you receive messages.  Check this option only when the Include me 
option is <emph>not<\emph> set.  This option identifies all known occurrences 
of your name so Mailer can eliminate them in the message address when you
reply to all the addressees.
<\list>

